review_blob: the barrel flavors spike in and out providing a glimpse of whats inside. There is not a distinct front, middle, end on this one. Tasty nonetheless.
slight spice heat and cinnamon bomb at the front, coffee and sweet spice rounds out the back end. delicious!
Big blackberry jam on the front. As we get further into this a prominent pepper note comes in. Alcohol well-hidden. Nice
Backlog. Maybe a chocolate pecan ale would be better. Not quite enough sweetness to balance off the astringency and flavor of the pecan ( skins)
Pretty dry as expected, astringent, spicy & resinous. Alcohol seems well-hidden, easy-drinking
None overpowering, balanced coconut with roast. Chocolate, moderate mouthfeel, looks prett.
From back in 2011. Completely sour. Barrel character is weak and does not come thru. I dont know what it is about rum barrels and infections but another one goes down.

beer_brewer_name: Port Brewing Co / The Lost Abbey
review_blob: a bit horsey, more funk than I remember from 2 yrs ago. Citrus, apple, apricot, lemon. holding up pretty well. I remember writing hay in my notes years ago but that seems to have faded now.
from months ago. acidity out front, berries and currants in the background. pinkish color. pretty clean and tart. astringency I always relate to blackberries.
Alaskan does this one up proper. smoke is there in full effect but you arent left as if you were licking burnt wood. The base porter is tasty and plays well with the treatment.
starts out green turning into citrus aromas. just a little biscuit in there with some mouthfeel. balanced approach in bitterness and aromas.

starts off very well, with a roast, chocolate impy stout and just a touch of the sour side. As I got into it though it did not quite sit right. not really sure I can put into words. definitely worth a try if you come across this one. I think most people will find it polarizing-love or hate.

I think of elderberry as a very European flavor. If you have not experienced a homemade elderberry cordial you are missing out and might not get the full effect of this beer. Really captures the light floral and citrus notes. Very refreshing, covers up some of the funk I expect from Cantillon. I forgot how good this is.

had to get this b/c it was in a can. My tastes may have changed a bit or perhaps I am comparing to different Rodenbach I have had years prior. Flavors seem a bit muted overall, comparatively. very approachable beer and for the price was a good bet.
an OK beer but nothing too extraordinary to talk about. thought the hops were faded but the bottle age is questionable/unknown though assume it to be only a month or two.
perhaps my favorite RR. I am a fan of quality oaked Chardonnay so perhaps that contributes. Light, balanced acidity and sour, oak is there but not over-powering. drink this all day.
I actually thought this was pretty straightforward for a Mikkeller collab. A well done stout, the licorice was not prominent. I didn;t really get much of the berries.
realized it was already winter when this popped on the shelves. a fine, drinkable IPA, skews a bit more bitter than aromatic, somewhat more malt character than some of its counterparts.

HUGE coffee for me here though other reviews dont seem to reflect this. The vanilla was very faint if at all and I cant say I got much wood. However, those components most likely merely served to make up the balance of this beer which was fantastic. Moderate body, big chocolate.
kinda nutty with big malt character, green, resin, piney hop aromas come through strong. pretty easy-drinkin at 9.5%
some citrus but primarily piney/green hop aromas, no real alcohol notes to speak of, quaffable for 9%, goes down easy.
2008-I like port and I like this brew. Mild English barleywine malty character, smooth, moderate body with nice sweetness on the back end and in the nose.

pumpkinator 2012. a nice beer but I was hoping it skewed a little more toward the stout side. I think I was just bored with pumpkin beers for the season by the time I got to this. One of the better pumpkin beers for the year though.
beer_name: Saint Arnold Pumpkinator Imperial Pumpkin Stout

review_blob: nice balance, clever name, just a touch of spice, yeast is there but not over the top banana or bubble gum. Extremely quaffable canned hefe/witbier.
clean, dry with just the touch of sulfur I expect in a fine pilsner. Some floral/noble hops and just a touch of malt.
always a fan of rye IPA done right and this is no exception. Hops arent huge here and the rye adds just enough to balance it out.
thought this was decent IPA, though tame & reserved. could add some extra hops on the dry-hopping to kick up the aromatics a bit.
there is a fine balance of black malts for me and my Black IPAs. This one is over the line. Just not my style. The acrid malts overshadow the hops.
not bad but bitter and high roast. need to tame it down a bit to make it more approachable. more chocolate less black malt
on tap @ Arcadia. Balanced malt-forward, may be dangerous and sneak up on you at 8%. Better than expected.
the vanilla comes thru quite strongly then bourbon then choco. Heavy but not syrupy, sweet but not quite a "dessert beer". plenty of caramel to go around.
I did NOT realize this was a saison while drinking. I considered this more of a pale ale. Just a slight yeasty/bready component otherwise it was light, drinkable, with decent hop character.
beer_name: Russian River It Takes A Lot Of Great Beer To Make Great Wine

review_blob: not a bad beer, nothing too distinct about it. Reminded me of a Yuengling or something with a little bit of wheat and grassy character to it.
very low carbonation, overall the beer flavor is a bit flat as well. rich chocolate, smoke and peppers.
reminds me of barely sour-ish apple juice. Easy-drinking, rather sweet, nice on a hot Florida day. Little sour but good flavor overall
beer_name: Jester King Bonnie the Rare Berliner Weisse

review_blob: probably my least favorite of the Japanese big boys. weak, light body, lacking flavor, what flavor is there is nothing exciting.
a fantastic beer saved to celebrate the birth of my baby girl. Tart cherries abound. Lacking the harsh acidity that some sour brown ales can give off. Extremely drinkable, worth searching out.
great hop aroma and really not all that bitter for a DIPA considering some of the others. This is inline with my preference of strong citrus and green hop aromatics IPAs
Tart cherry, juicy, menthol, cough syrup, very fruity flanders red. not oversly funky or all that sour

my least favorite of the 3 JK/Mikkeller stout collabs. This is good but was lacking compared to the other 2. smooth, oily, rich mouthfeel. moderate coffee melds well with roasted malts. chipotle seem muted compared to the others.
beer_name: Jester King / Mikkeller Beer Geek Rodeo

review_blob: pretty weak offering, the least enjoyable of this mix pack. Missing the maltiness I was expecting. it will do the job but I expected better.
all malt character/flavor here. Body seemed bit thin. pretty easy-drinking and seems like the barrel treatment might make this one absolutely stellar.

a gusher but not infected. Mild flavors abound. A nice beer with god balance but maybe I was expecting something to pop a bit more. that being said, one I would surely drink again. The pecan adds a nice astringency to complement the vanilla & whiskey finish.
beer_name: (512) Whiskey Barrel Aged Double Pecan Porter

review_blob:
2012 - a bit hot but still pretty sweet, smooth an rich
2006 - very mellow, low carbonation, considerably diff than fresh. big chocolate, moderate roast without bitterness, sweet bourbon

vibrant pink color, little head. Fantastic aroma, fairly balanced between fruit and sour. Not nearly as sour as some describe, fruit aroma is much stronger than the flavor. seems like the base beer is muted a bit with the addition of the fruit.
beer_name: Russian River Framboise for a Cure (2011-2012)

review_blob: light, pretty easy-drinking. Not what I would call real grape flavor but rather a pleasant fruity note in the background.
big raspberry in the nose, some cherry skin/pit perhaps? The brown beer adds a nice body and rounds it out pretty well.
2011- thick & syrupy, fairly dry, seems to be a mineral aspect that I cant quite place. Kind of a strange aftertaste.
rather lacking for what I was expecting from this. I get the malt but missing the caramelization I would have liked. has a dry sweetness to it.
beer_name: The Bruery / Taps Provisions Series: A Steins Throw

review_blob: by the last bottle of the 4-pack spread over 2 weeks I liked this less and less. I think I am out-growing this style. Drinkable brew but the spices are overdone for me
